Location is nice, almost all parcels have shadow and it is a good place for snorkeling. Two little cobblestone beaches, sea inflatable games (fee), boat slide, and fast food, convenience store and a little greengrocer. Camp is affiliated with schools, so there could be music and games, not later than 11PM.  If you need extra tranquillity, you can camp outside parcels, 100m away from the sea under the pines. Wide meadow for playing.
Eating outside alert: fast food use to shut down at 9:30PM and other restaurants in the area seem to have the same schedule, even in high season.
Camp prices are a little below the average; boat rental (pedal boat 25 euros an hour) and water games rather expensive (bring your own SUP).

Grass and ground surface parking with almost no shadow. Showers with token. Toilets are free (as far as I remember). The whole area is subject to mosquitos after sunset. The site features one of the few remaining natural beaches of northern Adriatic, known as "La Brussa". Beach is sandy and cleaned at the beginning of summer. Shadowed paths in the wood.

This camp site is located in a very beautiful environment, close to nature, but also close to the city. The reception wasn't overly friendly (German: "norddeutsche Freundlichkeit"), but since we weren't here to make friends, that's probably okay.

The toilets are clean, our pitch however reeked a bit of, well, "animal poo", but we did not spend too much time on our pitch, so that's something we could live with. For roughly 22 Euros per night for two people, this is an "okay" camp site.

Since we only wanted to stay one night and did not need any electricity, we were allowed to use the camper van area at the entrance of the camp site for roughly 15 Euros per night. What a bargain! The showers and restrooms were very, very clean, as were the pitches, and the nice "Stübchen" (a small bistro with fast food and beverages) was a nice extra. In addition, the owners were super-friendly, warm-hearted and very welcoming. Shoutout to Jürgen! We'll visit again if we're ever in the area.

Friendly camp site with nice pitches. The restrooms and showers were clean and the price (20 EUR per night) was more than fair. Maastricht can be visited either by bike (roughly half an hour) or via train.

Nice big dog park with gravel paths between lush lawns and huge trees.

The dog part is not actually fenced off. But is it part of the Søndermarken park, making up about almost half of it. And Søndermarken park is mostly fenced in except for the exits.  In particular there is a fence towards the south end at Valby Langgade. So you have to keep track of where you dog can be off leash (check any of the information boards) but you do not have to worry much about you four legged friend running onto the road.

It is big dog park (7 ha) with lots of trees, bushes, grass, flowers, etc.  There is a small muddy pond in the middle
There are no waste bins, so you either have to carry your poop bags back home or not pick up after your dog (this is the posted rules, which some people does read, because there is a pile of full bags on the ground at the entrance)

There is no drinking water. But there a picnic table in each end.
The park is shaped like a triangle with the railroad on one side, the motorway on another side, and the Copenhagen shooting range on the third side. So there is some noise. But not so much that the dogs care about it. And it might be good for some dogs to get used to gunshots.

Parking is at the end of Selinevej which is convenient if you travel on the Øresundsmotorway.

Solid camping site. We used a pitch that did not have electricity included, which was exactly what we needed. The toilets were - for the most part - clean. A few pitches (ours included) are near the table tennis table, where teenagers gathered and were a bit loud. That did not affect our stay in a negative way, however. Just be aware of your surroundings if that is something that is important to you.

A bonus point is given for the toilet paper that we were supplied with during check-in, as well as a complementary garbage bag.

Very relaxing site with chilled owners! ✌️ Instead of regular pitches, everyone is free to setup camp wherever they want. The place boasts some trees, so it is easy to find some shade. The toilets lack toilet paper, but are otherwise very clean. There are enough sinks for everyone, and it's even possible to use a washing machine. Electricity is also available (for a small fee), as is an outdoor pool (no additional fee). Since its roads and ways are unlit, the site becomes quite dark at night, so depending on how close to the toilets you stay, it's good to have a flashlight around.

Tip: At 6 PM, a small "restaurant" opens right next to the main camping ground, where olives, bread, cold beer and wine is served. That area feels like straight from a relaxing "festival", with makeshift sofas and comfy chairs. We highly recommend you visit here, especially before sunset.

We were looking for a space to organize our Openstreetmap mapathon and HSBXL was very open to letting us use their space. I must say Wouter, who was overseeing the space at the time, was VERY welcoming. Noticed I was wearing a mask (no requirement at the time of writing this) and immediately asked if he should open a window for me (to get some fresh air).

The space itself is (at the time of writing) located in a pretty cool and unique location, an old office building. It definitely fits with the hackerspace feel. At first it seems hard to find but when you enter the courtyard it's located at, you immediately realize you're at the right place. As with most hackerspaces, I assume(?), the fridge/snackstorage works with a trust system where you just deposit the money of whatever you take. (you can pay with cash, bankcard, bank transfer).

It's a shame this location might disappear by the end of the year, but i'm sure they'll find something with a similar vibe!

Hier een fiets gekocht: verkopers waren zeer vriendelijk. Kleine problemen bij de aankoop zelf:
A) Verkopers spraken elkaar tegen (volgens de een zaten er pedalen bij, volgens de ander niet; volgens de een moest er een andere fietsstandaard gemonteerd worden, volgens de ander paste degene die standaard geleverd werd)
B) De fiets werd niet goed afgesteld: zadel werd ruwweg correct geplaatst maar al de andere afmetingen moest ik zelf zien in te stellen.
C) De montage is niet zo goed uitgevoerd: zip-ties waren niet afgeknipt, schijfremmen niet ingebed, waarschuwingsfolie niet verwijderd.

Ik zou het liefst 2,5 sterren geven (5/10) maar aangezien dit niet mogelijk is, en de problemen toch ook niet min zijn (niet ingebedde schijfremmen vormen een reëel gevaar) kan ik de fietsenwinkel toch niet echt aanbevelen en geeft ik 2/5 sterren.

WERDEN NIE MEHR KOMMEN!

Waren am Samstag, 11.9.2021 dort (2 Erwachsene, 2 Jungs 7+9 Jahre.)
Bei der Talstation: Aus Geiz ist niemand unten in der Talstation, der die Gäste empfängt auch keine Kasse.
Oben mussten die Kinder erst auf die Toilette - man glaubt es nicht: von einer unfreundlichen, alten Frau wird man erst unhöflich angeschnauzt man müsse erst zahlen (dann sollen sie halt schon in der Talstation die entsprechende Infrastruktur hinstellen.
Als wir dann Trottinetts mieten wollten, die gleiche hässige Frau wieder: Sie müssen erst einmal den Zettel dort ausfüllen und dann komme ich, wenn ich Zeit habe (sorry, sie hätte gar nicht erst weg müssen und uns gleich bedienen).
Zusammen haben wir 106.- für eine 15-minütige Talfahrt (inkl. Gondel) bezahlt und mussten im Tal selber die Trottinetts in die Gondeln einräumen (und dafür warten bis wieder Gondeln unten waren).

NICHT ZU EMPFEHLEN
ALLE UNFREUNDLICH, DIE TROTTINETT QUITSCHEN, MANN MUSS ALS KUNDE SELBER ARBEIT

Der Stellplatz wurde im April 2021 gebaut, Ver- und Entsorgung (die ein bisschen abseits an der Bulauhalle liegt) ist daher topmodern, inklusive Bodeneinlass. Sehr angenehm. 100 Liter Wasser kosten 1 €. Der Stellplatz selbst ist kostenlos, nur wer Strom möchte, muss zahlen (1 € für 2 kWh). Der Boden ist relativ eben, aber geschottert, was immer ein bisschen Schweinerei bedeutet. Das, zusammen mit dem öfter mal auftretenden Gebell von der Hundewiese und dem Geballer vom Schützenhaus nebenan führt zu einem Stern Abzug, aber ansonsten echt ein netter Platz. Die Bäume spenden ein bisschen Schatten, haben aber teilweise auch recht niedrige Äste. Die Straße direkt am Platz ist mäßig befahren, nachts ist hier gar nichts mehr los und der Platz ist sehr ruhig. Oh, und er ist beleuchtet. Der Wald direkt nebenan lädt zum Spazieren oder Geocachen ein. Alles in allem: empfehlenswert.

RÅG sets themselves apart from the rest of cafes in Uddevalla, with their alternative vibes in both interior design and food menu. For example they don't serve regular soft drinks like coke or pepsi, instead you'll find craft soda, kombucha and beer, all coming from micro breweries in Sweden. One of the rooms often have Artwork for sale, which is a collaboration between RÅG and local artists. There are some good vegan options but if RÅG wants a 5 star rating from me, they need to expand those options further. Also the coffee could be a little better. The staff are nice people and have given me free dessert on several occasions.

W czasie budowy pałacu oraz z okazji jego otwarcia polska ekipa nakręciła kolorowe filmy (Ślubujemy 1952, Powrót na Stare Miasto 1954, Niedzielny poranek 1955), a zagraniczni fotoreporterzy (np. John H. Schultz ze Stanów Zjednoczonych i Paul Almasy z Francji) wykonali kolorowe fotografie, dzięki czemu znany jest wygląd czystego, nowego Pałacu Kultury i Nauki oraz jego ogromnych, drewnianych i niesczerniałych jeszcze okien.

W 1956 rozpoczęła się seria samobójczych skoków z tarasu widokowego na 30 piętrze, na wysokości 114 metrów – najpierw skoczył Francuz, po nim jeszcze siedmiu Polaków. Po tych incydentach zdecydowano się na założenie krat na tarasie.
Ruim aanbod, vlotte service

2020-11-10 Besuch der Anlage. Am Punkt, wie er in OSM ausgewiesen wird, ist kein Hinweis darauf zu finden, dass dort jemals etwas war. Das ganze Gebiet im Umkreis von etwa 100 m wurde abgeschritten und genau geprüft. Keine Mauerreste, keine kleinsten Erhebungen oder Senken konnten gefunden werden. Einziger Hinweis ist die LIDAR-Auswertung als Hillshade (Foto). Dort findet man eine feine Struktur, die daruf hinweisen könnte, dass dort mal was war (feine Kreuze als Markierungen auf dem Hillshadebild.

Über die Burgstelle sind sehr wenige Informationen verfügbar:
Gemeinde Boppelsen: 
.... Die de Bobpinsolo's sollen eine Burg an der Lägern bewohnt haben, doch fehlen bis anhin jegliche Spuren einer solchen Behausung. ...
Ortsbegehung am 8. November 2020:
Der Ort ist schwer zu finden, da mitten im Waldgebiet. Jedoch mit Hilfe von QField, OSM und einer Hillshade, DTM 2014, Kt. Zürich, 50cm, konnte der Ort identifiziert werden. Dort nur Bäume und Gebüsch. Keine einzige bedeutende Überhöhung konnte identifiziert werden. Es sind auch keine Steine zu finden, die auf ein Gemäuer hinweisen. Auch wurde die Umgebung mit einem Radius von ca. 100m untersucht. Jedoch auch dort keinen kleinsten Hinweis auf ein früheres Gebäude.

It is still not clear where exactly the location was. To have something in the hand I created from the DTM 2014 50cm of the canton Zürich a hillshade of the place. Maybe this will help for further investigation.

Google is one of the most innovative and visionary companies on the planet and they have significantly shaped how we interact with the internet today. However, Google is found again and again to abuse its dominance that it gained through its ingenuity to put its competitors at a disadvantage, thus further increasing their dominance. I admire the work that Google is doing and I am an enthusiastic user of many of their products such as the G Suite, Maps, and of course the Search. Yet, I strongly advocate for the creation of alternative technologies so that we don't end up in lock-in and dependence one day.

Der, mit 1141 Metern, höchste Berg im Harz ist das Ausflugsziel im südwestlichen Niedersachsen. Die Startpunkte für die Wanderungen zum Gipfel sind aus allen Richtungen mit dem öffentlichen Personennahverkehr als auch mit dem Individualverkehr sehr gut zu erreichen.

Wanderwege
Das Wegenetz des Harzes hat für alle Erfahrungsstufen etwas zu bieten. Ob es sich um einen absoluten Anfänger handelt, der nur zum Brocken möchte und auf dem Rückweg die Brockenbahn verwendet oder der erfahrene Fernwanderer, der sich auf einer der vielen Fernwanderrouten, die den Harz kreuzen, befindet.

Klimatische Besonderheiten
Der Harz hat auf Grund seiner Lage auf klimatisch einiges zu bieten. Während es in den Tälern rund um den Brocken angenehmes Wetter haben kann sieht es auf dem Brocken oftmals ganz anders aus. Ohne wetterfeste Kleidung und entsprechendes Schuhwerk würde ich den Aufstieg nicht wagen.

Wanderwege für alle Erfahrungsstufen und gute Erreichbarkeit

Sehr interessanter Ort und absolut einen Besuch wert! Wirklich inspirierend und bewundernswert so viel Natur in solch interessanter Weise in die Stadt zu bringen. Etwas mehr Sitzgelegenheiten wären schön, sodass man noch mehr Zeit hier verbringen kann.

Wir sind in Wolfenschiessen gestartet, dann mit der Luftseilbahn Brändlen hoch. Von Brändlen über den Haldigrat bis zum Brisen aufgestiegen. Auf dem Weg zurück ins Tal über die andere Seite haben wir einen spektakulären Platz für unser Zelt gefunden. Eine windige Nacht, aber die Aussicht auf Sonnenuntergang und den Sonnenaufgang am Morgen haben für alles entlohnt.

Wir waren hier am ersten Schneetag dieses Jahr im September. Weil viel Schnee war sind wir von Stoos aus mit dem Lift hochgefahren. Ein sehr angenehmes Erlebnis, und die Aussicht oben absolut atemberaubend! Eine Woche später sind wir noch einmal zurück gekommen, der Schnee war größtenteils weg und wir konnten mühelos wandern und die Aussicht geniessen. Nun sind wir von Stoos zu Klingenstock hoch gewandert und dann den Grat entlang bis Fronalpstock. Ein wunderbares Erlebnis!

Agree that reviews can be a fairly fundamental building block of our communication. The current standard is fairly flexible and should be able to incorporate a wide variety of use-cases: https://mangrove.reviews/standard
At the same time we would like to keep it somewhat focused for now, until it gets a bit of traction, its hard to get it going for all things at the same time while maintaining ok quality.

There is already some local caching, but we currently do not save it to more persistent local storage. It should not be hard though with the current front-end setup. It is best to submit issues for discussion here: https://gitlab.com/plantingspace/mangrove or even contribute directly :)

also hoping for 2 new features: review of anything (although i'm currently wishing just for movies) and editing...

on a second thought, this whole concept have a much bigger potential by not forcing a previous connection and, instead, making the effort to reduce redundancy clutter with ai and reporting, to identify if different topics are actually the same, or separate mistakes...

if you think the internet is made of basically 3 mediums:
- notes . website, docs, wiki
- logs . messaging, email, forums, articles
- ether . videos, calls, games
and that we don't really have an easy decentralised format for "notes", mangrove could focus on that instead! i'm probably just too excited with this and forgetting other initiatives that must be way ahead in this aspect... #wishfulthinking 😁

(delta chat have a great grasp for logs, fwiw imho and ether is meant to be an eternal area looking for improvements, anyway).

unique. the login idea is genial! i really hope it'll catch on, so much better than freaking centralised openid. it's a beta, got some expected amount of bugs. the 2 biggest improvements it needs are: a better rating ( just an alpha idea cregox.net/rating ) and #offlinefirst, which includes of course many ways to real #backup (automated redundancy, origins of the internet anyone?). i'm also really glad how responsive and well this works on mobile #mobilefirst (another common misconception of most of the web today is that everyone owns a desktop).

bought the cheapest ticket from portugal to finland in february 2020 for july. about 200 eur. obviously i wasn't aware of covid19 yet. tried many times to contact them to resolve the issue. terrible customer support, phone drops, nobody seemed to care. nope, they would not cancel and refund my ticket before hand, regardless of such a situation! eventually they cancelled the flight, and my ticket, but didn't refund my money. took me almost 1 month to get a confirmation from them that i will be refunded. now, almost 2 months later, i'm still waiting to see just how much they'll pay back... they even offered 20% more to get a voucher instead, but i have no plans to fly with them anymore. sadly, they've got monopoly in portugal, so i might eventually find my only option will be to not just not fly... not too bad for the carbon emissions, at least! 🤣

Private bank in Switzerland. Nice design of branches and service, but when it comes to anything touching their IT setup, its pretty bad. Repeated mistakes when registering changes to accounts, intermittent breakage of mobile app, outdated credit card points scheme where you are being mailed pieces of paper to collect.
They fail to be reliable in the most basic cases, either due to poor IT or lack of transparent rules.

Content: well-researched, comprehensive review of the current state of accumulation and usage of personal data by corporations and governments. Shows the dystopian future into which we might be headed if we don't make changes. Risk assessments could be more balanced though to show also the opportunities. 
Style: insights could be compressed into much less text. The length of the book and the sometimes pretentious writing style might make it less accessible to a broader audience, which is a pity.

We went here for breakfast and it turned out to be a real hidden gem in terms of coziness and beautiful interior. Food was ok, we had an omelette with pickled veggies, topped with grated cheese. The regular omelette without the pickles is probably better. Service was very nice and the atmosphere was relaxed and cheerful.

It is a very nice walk up Gellert Hill, through a large park with windy paths and sculptures along the way. On top, you have a fantastic view over Budapest. A variety of stalls offering drinks and snacks makes it a great afternoon or early evening tour, especially on a warm and sunny day.

Nice vegan restaurant serving vegan versions of traditional Hungarian meals and more. Great for anyone who wants to explore the local cuisine without meat. Interior was well-maintained but looked a bit old-fashioned. But the food and great service made up for it.

Cozy historical village on the Tihany peninsula on the northern shore of Lake Balaton. Very well maintained and a real tourist magnet for the whole of Hungary. The village's website offers a downloadable pocket guide, a video and even a virtual tour. Besides the beautiful landscape one can enjoy the relics of the folk architecture such as the peasant houses. Had a great traditional meal at the Gulyas Udvar Etterem. Might become very crowded during high season (in March it was perfect though).

Had lunch here during our visit of Tihany, a picturesque historical village on a peninsula of Lake Balaton. This restaurant might look very touristic from outside, but inside you find a truly traditional cozy place that serves simple and very well-made local food, such as the cod paprikas I had. The waiter was very engaged and pleasant, and helped us to find the right meal according to our tastes. It was a great experience.

Great restaurant serving traditional gulyas and paprikas. Elegant and cozy industrial-style interior. Had two vegetarian dishes: one with giant white beans, topped with a fried egg and fresh peppers and onions that was fantastic. Second dish was good, but the mushrooms were a bit watery, so it was not as great as the bean dish. Great white wine recommendation (Tokaji) that fit perfectly.

Went here for breakfast and loved the food! Creative vegetarian/vegan options. Had dishes with oven-roasted pumpkin and another one with sweet potato, topped with different veggies or eggs/salmon. The coffee was great, too. Interior is cozy and interesting with the gallery, but overall quite small. At some point there was a queue of people ordering directly at the counter, which filled up the whole room.

Large historic indoor market in Budapest, built in 1897 and renovated in 1997. The architecture alone is already worth a visit. Very nice to wander around the many food stalls with local produce or popular Hungarian food items, eateries, souvenir shops.
Recht teuer. Laugengebäck ist ordentlich.

Static website generator in Julia. Still new, but quite enjoyable to use. Makes it really easy to include evaluated Julia code including plots. Supports good chunk of markdown including some useful extensions. Reasonable defaults. Still a bit clunky in the CLI workflow and smaller tooling ecosystem than JS. Good for static sites if you are into Julia ecosystem.

Best federated, open source messaging app out there. Fairly easy to use, allows servers with customised rules, supports end to end encryption, flexible room membership. Still has some UX issues with key management for encrypted channel and with poor loading performance both on the web and mobile.

Nice dashboard for tracking coronavirus. Seems to make use of reliable data and plots daily changes as well as log-scale cases. It would greatly benefit from showing cases per capita (or 100000 residents), rather than just numbers per country. Also the graphs do not allow zoom or finer ticks (to better see the rates).

Nice language for scientific computing - good performance, flexible type system and descent meta-programming. Main issues are with packages: slow load-times and still small ecosystem them (though growing well thanks to the type system). Some syntax and structuring of projects with modules feels a bit hacky.

Cool shelter located 1700mts high on the top of Cerro Catedral with an amazing 12km hike passing through forests, hills, and cliffs with the flowers and clear water. It has it all for the beginner hikers. Great in Spring/Summer seasons, when you can see the forest in between at its best. Make sure to take water and a walking stick along with some snacks for the way. The last hour can be tricky, as it is super steep. Wanna sleep/camp there? book in advance: http://refugiofreybariloche.com/

If you are in Buenos Aires and want to get away from all the noise, this small town is the perfect place for a day of relax and history. Disputed between the Spanish and Portuguese Crowns until almost the end of the XVIII century, it is the perfect plan for a day (by boat from Bs As or car/bus from Montevideo), where you can see the colonial architecture and enjoy the food and the sun. Make sure to check the Raddisson Hotel's pool if it is too warm! :D

Almost all soccer clubs in Buenos Aires have restaurants: this is the typical Neighbourhood club restaurant in the city, where you will be able to grasp the neighbourhood culture and how much people care about their sports club - especially if they play soccer there! great food! good quality and very friendly staff! 

Not so good if you don't eat meat: they do not have so many options for vegetarians.

Great place to try good plates that combines the best of Argentinian and Italian food tradition - good environment and really cheap. Try the "milanesa" if you eat meat and the "canelones" if you are a vegetarian. After 9pm you will need to queue, so make sure to either book in advance or go beforehand - and be careful: the sizes are really big! you can definitely share a portion.

Great for groups, families and friends, if you are looking for something romantic this is not the place to go.

Definitely one of the best views in Bariloche, you can reach the top of cerro Campanario either by foot (easy level hike) or cablecar - the ticket is around 3 EUR. Definetely worth it if you want to check the lakes around Bariloche and get an idea of the extension of The Andes. 

The Cerro is right at the start of "Circuito Chico": a 24km road through mountains full of hiking trails. So a good idea is always to wake up early, get to the top fo the mountain, and at around 11am start the Circuito.
An extension to PostgreSQL for spacial data. Pretty good documentation and a lot of options. Things work as expected. Requires some understanding of the different geospatial representation formats.
Beautiful city, a lot of culture to explore. And fantastic selection of restaurants, from traditional Polish food to exotic options such as Peruvian.

Visited the castle in winter, so it was a bit cold. Can only imagine how amazing it must be on a sunny day, with the lake around and the walls warmed by the sun. It was a fantastic experience to wander through its many rooms, and discover historical artifacts from its history spanning a whole millennium. Was touched by the story of François Bonivard who was imprisoned there and inspired a poem of Lord Byron: The Prisoner of Chillon.

Great Peruvian fusion food, fantastic drinks, and nice atmosphere! Interior is decorated with a lot of wood, dark green colours, and plants. The red drink on the picture was a delicious, interesting non-alcoholic hot drink with fresh raspberry and rosemary.

Visited a wonderful organ concert in this church on Sunday 2nd Feb. The concert took place on the organ-gallery, a loft that can be reached over stairs. I was impressed with the acoustics and the quality of the performance. Learned later that the church has been designated to cultural and spiritual events, and as a place for community gatherings, under the name CityKircheZug. Will definitely visit other cultural events here in the future.

Visited the Van Gogh Alive exhibition at Maag yesterday. Great experience in terms of sound and light quality. From the outside and also inside the building could benefit from modernisation to make it more welcoming.
Very nice town to visit: beautiful old town, nice modern art museum, views on Rigi, Pilatus and the lake.

Bürgenstock is great for a day trip from Zurich, Luzern or Zug. Nice trails on top for walks, and amazing view over alps and Lake Lucerne. Also, quite a few fine dining restaurants around, as well as a spa.

Nice destination for a hike up from the town of Zug. Hike takes around 2 hours and gives a beautiful view on the Zuger lake. On top there is a restaurant with simple local food to enjoy before hiking back down again. Good views on the alps, on some days you can even see Eiger, Jungfrau and Mönch.

We are using Open Collective for our open-source, non-profit project to receive donations and to manage our finances transparently for all contributors to see where money comes from and where it goes. It works pretty well for us so far.

We had the two vegetarian options on the menu and they were both very interesting and refined dishes. A bit too much grains for us, especially in the mushroom porridge, but nevertheless balanced and interesting tastes. Atmosphere also nice with large glass windows and a minimalist retro decor.

I regularly eat at this fantastic Thai restaurant. They have a bar downstairs which the restaurant shouldn't be confused with. The food is pretty authentic and there are sufficient vegetarian options. The restaurant is located in a historic and well kept house that displays original wood covered walls, with windows towards the lake. A pleasure for the eye as well.

We hiked up to Gütsch on a winter afternoon when it was already getting dark. Had a beautiful view over Lucerne from there. The restaurant also looks very nice, but didn't have the time to visit it. 
Next time we will definitely visit the little sculpture park there as it seemed interesting (closes at 18:00). For the way down we took the little funicular. Definitely recommend for a day trip to Luzern.

Great to see that mainstream media is showing true dedication for Privacy on the internet! Can totally recommend NYT's The Privacy Project newsletter and website.
